00:33:31.980 --> 00:33:33.060
have to start them, right?

00:33:33.100 --> 00:33:41.940
So you have to say asyncio create task, or you have to await it, because if you don't create a task or await it, it just doesn't run, it's an unrun async coroutine, right?

00:33:43.180 --> 00:33:43.540
Okay.

00:33:43.640 --> 00:33:58.380
So you've got to await it, and up to Python 3.11, this code was you would just say, okay, now it's on the background queue, and it's going to do its async await run, just as if you had awaited it, but you get to carry on and welcome the user, or whatever

00:33:58.380 --> 00:33:58.840
you're doing.

00:34:00.560 --> 00:34:05.820
Well, and this has been this way since 3.6, maybe 3.5, right?

00:34:05.860 --> 00:34:14.160
So that's a lot, it's like seven years, but now Python 3.12 onward, you can't do this anymore.

00:34:14.500 --> 00:34:26.040
If you do this, that task that was just started, you say async.io create task is eligible for garbage collection in the next line of code, and it might not even start.

00:34:27.360 --> 00:34:41.320
So I wanted to put that out there for people, like, you know, if you have this type of code, you had better look at it, you would better make a change, because for whatever reason, the async event loop now holds weak references to

00:34:41.320 --> 00:34:44.900
the tasks that it runs, and that doesn't just apply to this pattern.

00:34:44.900 --> 00:34:59.100
anything that somehow puts something into that task, that work queue, the loop, needs to keep track of it explicitly or else it potentially gets deleted out of

00:34:59.100 --> 00:35:00.020
memory, right?

00:35:00.020 --> 00:35:14.780
So if you look at the documentation for, what is it, create task in the docs, it says it's going to wrap a coroutine

00:35:14.780 --> 00:35:18.360
into a task and schedule its execution and return the task object.

00:35:18.660 --> 00:35:26.520
However, in Python 3.12 onward, it's important that you save a reference to the result to avoid the task disappearing mid-execution.

00:35:26.520 --> 00:35:28.420
that's new.

00:35:28.940 --> 00:35:31.160
So anyway, so what is the fix?

00:35:31.320 --> 00:35:35.060
You create this weird set that holds all running tasks that you're not tracking.

00:35:35.940 --> 00:35:38.140
You add it to that task, that set.

00:35:38.640 --> 00:35:47.500
Then you kick it off as a, or you kick it off as background work and you add the task there, and then you set up a callback that when the task is done, it takes it out of the set.

00:35:47.980 --> 00:35:48.920
So I don't know.

